  <h1>Fagor Commercial Dishwasher Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>Fagor Industrial is a Spanish commercial equipment manufacturer — part of the Onnera Group, itself a member of Spain's Mondragon Corporation cooperative. This matters for one practical reason: when Fagor Electrodomésticos (the consumer division) went bankrupt in 2013, many operators assumed the brand disappeared. It didn't. <strong>Fagor Industrial and Fagor Commercial continued operating</strong>, and their commercial dishwashers — the COP undercounter series, the AD door-type line, the LP conveyor series — are still widely deployed throughout SoCal's restaurant, hotel, and catering kitchens. If you have a Fagor Commercial unit and are struggling to find a technician who actually knows the equipment, that's the source of the confusion.</p>

  <p>We service the full Fagor Commercial dishwasher line throughout Los Angeles, Orange County, Ventura County, and the Inland Empire. Same-day response. $120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair. Call <strong>{phone}</strong>.</p>

  <h2>Fagor Commercial Dishwasher Product Lines</h2>

  <h3>CO / COP Series — Undercounter Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>The COP series is Fagor's high-production undercounter line — the COP-504W EVO Concept+ being the most widely deployed model in SoCal bar and small restaurant environments. These machines run a <strong>dual-boiler architecture</strong>: a wash tank boiler maintains the cleaning temperature, while a separate rinse booster heater delivers the final sanitizing rinse at a 70°F rise above incoming water temperature. This design means the machine can sanitize effectively even with lower-temperature incoming hot water — but it also means there are two separate heating systems that can fail independently.</p>
  <p>The COP-504W runs IPX4 electronic controls with an ECO autofill system and soft-start wash pump protection. It produces 37 racks per hour with a 0.63 gallon-per-cycle rinse consumption via the EFFI linear rinse system. In LA's hard water environment — most municipal zones run 250–350 ppm TDS — the booster heater is the primary failure point. Limescale accumulates on the rinse booster heating element faster than on the wash tank element because the booster runs hotter and handles a smaller water volume. An undescaled COP-504W in LA water will show degraded final rinse temperatures within 4–6 months of operation.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> CO-502, CO-502W, CO-500, CO-523, COP-504, COP-504W, COP-504E, COP-504WE, COP-505, COP-505W, COP-174, COP-174W</p>

  <h3>AD Series — Door-Type / Hood Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>The AD series door-type machines are Fagor's mid-volume workhorse — the AD-48 and AD-125 handle 48 and 125 racks per hour respectively. Door-type machines see heavier use than undercounters and in SoCal restaurant kitchens they often run 10–14 hour shifts. The failure modes reflect that intensity: wash pump wear from continuous operation, pressure switch drift from scale accumulation in the pressure sensing line, and door gasket misalignment from the physical stress of repeated hood operation. The AD series uses a stamped one-piece stainless tank — durable, but when the tank thermostat drifts or the contactor controlling the tank heating element fails, wash temperature drops without an obvious external sign until dishes come out with visible food residue or a health inspector flags sanitization temperature.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> AD-48, AD-48W, AD-48E, AD-125, AD-125W, AD-125E, AD-125WE, AD-132, AD-133, AD-150, AD-200, AD-300</p>

  <h3>LP Series — Conveyor Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Fagor LP conveyor dishwashers are the high-volume solution — the LP-432 through LP-1200 series handle 432 to 1,200 racks per hour for hotel banquet operations, event catering facilities, stadium concession kitchens, and large institutional food service. These are complex machines with multiple wash and rinse zones, conveyor drive systems, and larger booster heater assemblies. When an LP conveyor fails during a banquet service or a stadium event day, the operational impact is severe. LP series repairs require understanding the full conveyor mechanism, the multi-zone temperature management, and the control board architecture — this is not undercounter dishwasher work.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> LP-432, LP-433, LP-442, LP-443, LP-700, LP-800, LP-900, LP-1100, LP-1200</p>

  <h2>Fagor Error Codes — What They Mean in SoCal</h2>

  <p>Fagor commercial dishwashers display alphanumeric error codes on the IPX4 control panel. Here are the codes we see most frequently in SoCal service calls, and what they actually indicate in this market's hard water environment:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Common SoCal Cause</th><th>First Action</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>E8 / BF</strong></td>
        <td>Boiler filling error — boiler failed to reach proper water level</td>
        <td>Water inlet solenoid valve partially blocked by mineral scale, or float switch stuck by limescale deposits</td>
        <td>Verify water pressure (20–60 PSI required), inspect inlet screen for scale, clean float assembly</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>F6</strong></td>
        <td>Heating failure — water not reaching temperature</td>
        <td>Booster heater element coated in limescale reducing heat transfer, or NTC probe drift, or PCB heater relay failure</td>
        <td>Check NTC probe resistance, inspect booster element for scale coating, test heater relay on PCB</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>F4</strong></td>
        <td>Flood / water level fault</td>
        <td>Float switch stuck in raised position from scale accumulation, or door seal misalignment causing false flood signal</td>
        <td>Clean float assembly, check door gasket alignment and seal integrity</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>D14</strong></td>
        <td>Fill failure — wash tank not filling</td>
        <td>Clogged solenoid inlet valve or blocked filter on incoming water line</td>
        <td>Clean inlet filter, test solenoid valve for proper actuation and flow</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>A note on F6 in LA specifically: the F6 heating error is the most common Fagor service call we receive in the SoCal market. The root cause in roughly 60% of cases is a booster heater element that's heavily scaled — the element is physically intact and electrically functional, but the limescale coating insulates the element surface from the water, preventing effective heat transfer. The machine runs, the element heats, but the water temperature doesn't rise fast enough to satisfy the NTC probe setpoint, triggering F6. The fix is descaling, not part replacement. Operators who replace the booster element without descaling the system will see F6 return within weeks.</p>

  <h2>The LA Hard Water Problem — Fagor Dishwashers Specifically</h2>

  <p>Los Angeles municipal water hardness varies by distribution zone, but most of the city and county runs between 250 and 350 ppm total dissolved solids. The San Gabriel Valley and parts of the South Bay run harder — some zones exceed 400 ppm. Fagor's COP undercounter series is particularly vulnerable to scale accumulation because of its booster heater architecture: the booster operates at higher temperatures than the wash tank heater, in a smaller water volume, with faster cycling. This creates the ideal conditions for rapid calcium carbonate precipitation onto the element surface.</p>

  <p>The commercial standard for Fagor undercounters in the LA market is <strong>monthly deliming</strong> with manufacturer-approved descaler — not quarterly, not "when problems appear." Machines running on LA water that are descaled monthly maintain consistent booster performance and rarely trigger F6. Machines descaled quarterly or less commonly will develop F6 errors, reduced final rinse temperatures, and eventually element failure. We find that most Fagor operators in LA are on a quarterly or semi-annual descaling schedule — the schedule recommended for lower-hardness markets — and are paying the cost in service calls.</p>

  <p>We also recommend and install <strong>inline water softener systems</strong> for high-volume Fagor installations. A properly sized softener before the dishwasher inlet reduces mineral load on both the wash tank and booster heater, extending element life and reducing descaling frequency.</p>

  <h2>Who Runs Fagor Commercial in SoCal</h2>

  <p><strong>Spanish and Mediterranean restaurants</strong> are the most concentrated Fagor operators in the LA market — the brand has strong market penetration in the segment that would naturally gravitate toward Spanish commercial kitchen equipment. Tapas bars from Silver Lake to Santa Monica, paella restaurants in the San Gabriel Valley, and Spanish hotel concepts in Beverly Hills and Downtown LA run Fagor COP undercounters and AD door-type machines as the kitchen standard.</p>

  <p><strong>Hotel banquet and event catering</strong> operations are where the LP conveyor series appears most frequently in SoCal. Properties along the Wilshire corridor, in Marina del Rey, and in the convention hotel cluster near LAX run LP series conveyors in their banquet dishroom operations. When these machines fail during a banquet setup, it's a significant operational event — we prioritize LP conveyor calls at the same urgency level as walk-in cooler failures.</p>

  <p><strong>Event catering companies</strong> operating out of Vernon, Commerce, and the Eastside production kitchen corridor also run Fagor LP equipment. Catering operations that produce 500–2,000 covers per event need the LP series throughput, and they need it to be reliable on event days when there's no margin for downtime.</p>

  <h2>Sanitization Compliance — What's Actually Required</h2>

  <p>California Retail Food Code requires commercial dishwashers to achieve a final rinse temperature of <strong>180°F at the rack surface</strong> for high-temperature sanitization, or an approved chemical sanitizer concentration for low-temperature machines. Fagor's COP and AD series are high-temperature machines — they rely on the booster heater to elevate rinse water to sanitizing temperature.</p>

  <p>When a Fagor booster heater is scaled or failing, the machine may complete cycles and appear to be functioning while delivering a final rinse below the 180°F threshold. Dishes look clean, pass visual inspection, but are not being sanitized to code. LA County Environmental Health inspectors use calibrated thermometers and surface temperature sensors — a machine running a 155°F final rinse instead of 180°F will fail inspection. We test final rinse temperature on every Fagor service call as part of our diagnostic process, not as an afterthought.</p>

  <h2>Recent Fagor Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"COP-504W showing F6, repeated resets not clearing — tapas bar West Hollywood"</h3>
  <p>Fagor COP-504W EVO Concept+, F6 heating error persistent through three power cycles. Previous service company had replaced the NTC probe 6 weeks earlier — F6 returned. Root cause on our visit: booster heater element heavily scaled, element resistance normal on multimeter (element electrically intact) but surface coated in calcium carbonate approximately 3mm thick. Performed full descale with approved Fagor descaler, verified element surface condition, confirmed final rinse temperature reaching 183°F. F6 has not returned in 4 months of follow-up. Technician note to the bar: the previous probe replacement was correct diagnosis for the code — wrong diagnosis for the cause. The probe was reading accurately. The booster wasn't heating the water fast enough. Set bar on monthly descaling protocol.</p>

  <h3>"AD-48 door-type — dishes not sanitizing, health inspection flag, Mid-City restaurant"</h3>
  <p>AD-48 door-type called in after a routine LA County health inspection flagged dishwasher sanitization temperature. Machine appeared to be cycling normally, no error codes. Final rinse temperature measured at 161°F — below the 180°F threshold. Tank thermostat had drifted 19°F low; machine was completing cycles at reduced temperature without triggering any error state. Replaced the tank thermostat assembly, verified wash temperature at 150°F and final rinse at 182°F. Descaled both tank and booster heater elements as part of the service visit. Restaurant passed re-inspection. This is exactly the failure mode that gets restaurants cited — the machine runs, no alarm, no obvious problem, but temperatures are out of compliance.</p>

  <h3>"LP-700 conveyor — intermittent conveyor drive failure, hotel banquet kitchen Downtown LA"</h3>
  <p>Fagor LP-700 conveyor dishwasher, conveyor drive stopping intermittently mid-cycle — 2 failures in the previous week during banquet service. Drive motor contactor was failing: contacts showing arcing and pitting from wear, contactor not consistently engaging under load. Replaced the drive motor contactor with OEM Fagor part, tested through 3 full conveyor cycles at full rack load. Inspected wash and rinse zone spray arms for scale — found partial blockage on the final rinse zone arms, cleaned. Hotel now on quarterly LP-series preventive maintenance contract.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>Is Fagor Commercial still in business after the 2013 bankruptcy?</strong><br>
  Yes. The 2013 bankruptcy affected Fagor Electrodomésticos — the consumer appliance division. Fagor Industrial and Fagor Commercial, which manufacture commercial kitchen equipment including dishwashers, continued operating as part of the Onnera Group. Commercial Fagor dishwashers are actively manufactured and supported with OEM parts availability.</p>

  <p><strong>My Fagor COP-504W is showing F6 — do I need a new heating element?</strong><br>
  Not necessarily. F6 on the COP-504W indicates the booster heater failed to raise rinse water temperature to setpoint. In LA's hard water environment, the most common cause is a scaled booster element — the element is physically intact but coated in limescale that prevents heat transfer. Before replacing any parts, the system should be descaled and the final rinse temperature tested. If temperature normalizes after descaling, the element is fine. Replacing the element without descaling will result in the same failure pattern within weeks.</p>

  <p><strong>How often should a Fagor dishwasher be descaled in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Monthly for undercounter COP series in LA's water. The manufacturer's standard recommendation assumes average water hardness. LA municipal water at 250–350 ppm TDS accelerates scale accumulation significantly — the monthly interval is the appropriate adjustment for this market. AD door-type machines: monthly descale of the booster, quarterly for the wash tank. LP conveyors: quarterly full descale with monthly inspection.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you carry OEM Fagor Commercial parts?</strong><br>
  We source OEM and verified compatible parts through the Fagor Commercial parts network. Common parts — booster heater elements, NTC probes, wash pump assemblies, door gaskets, inlet solenoid valves, and contactors for the COP and AD series — are stocked or available same-day from our parts network. LP conveyor parts may require 1–2 day sourcing for non-standard components.</p>

  <p><strong>What is your diagnostic fee?</strong><br>
  $120 commercial diagnostic, applied directly to the repair cost when you proceed.</p>

  <p><strong>Can you service Fagor LP conveyor dishwashers?</strong><br>
  Yes. LP series conveyor work is a commercial specialty requiring understanding of the multi-zone wash and rinse architecture, conveyor drive systems, and the larger booster heater assemblies. We service LP-432 through LP-1200 throughout the SoCal hotel and catering corridor.</p>

